@node Improving the Clone Detecting Algorithm
@chapter Improving the Clone Detecting Algorithm

The CodeStreamConsumer suffers from a few issues that makes it less suitable for Big Data. The most obvious issue is of course that it hangs (at least for me) before it finishes processing all the files even in the relatively small Qualitas Corpus. This really isn't very surprising, considering that the @code{FileStorage} class keeps all the processed files in memory. Not only that, to speed up processing it keeps a chunkified version of the file @emph{also} in memory, essentially doubling the memory footprint of every file.

In fact, most of the time the original file is not needed once the initial processing is done, so we can and should offload all of that into a database. Studying the @code{FileStorage} class, it can easily be seen how this might be done.

I leave it as an exercise to the avid student to implement and measure what retrieving every file from the database each time a new file arrives for processing will do for the processing times. A middle ground would be to store the original file but keep the chunks in memory. This would at least reduce the memory footprint down to just one instance of each file. This is an improvement, but still not very Big Data of us. We can do better.

