@node Hashing
@section Hashing

@cindex Hashing
@cindex Hash function
A seemingly unrelated issue is that every chunk comparison requires @code{CHUNKSIZE} comparisons of SourceLines. As it turns out, the next improvement solves both of these problems, i.e. fewer comparisons and smaller memory footprint. One approach to reduce complex data to a small fixed-size comparable unit is through @emph{hashing}. For example the music identification service Shahzam @uref{https://www.shazam.com/} uses hashing to store and match music (Nicely explained in a Youtube video @emph{How Shahzam Works}: @uref{https://youtu.be/kMNSAhsyiDg} ).

The trick with hashing (which, by the way, the @code{String.hashCode()} method in Java fails at) is that for every unique input the hash function produces a single unique fingerprint. Thus, the same input always produce the same output, and no two inputs (which are different) produce the same output. So rather than having to compare data of some arbitrary size (@code{CHUNKSIZE} of source code, @code{x} seconds of noise, or the DNA of an extinct reptile), it is enough to compare the generated hash code to determine if the original data is the same.

@example
+----------------------+
| Some lines of source |   
| data, for example    |   +------------+   +----------------------------------+
| a chunk of source    |-->| Hash       |-->| ede58a2363974547f4f0d2591352b1c9 |
| code.                |   | Function   |   +----------------------------------+
+----------------------+   +------------+
@end example

Learn more about hash functions:
@itemize
@item
Hashing: Why & How @uref{https://www.youtube.com/embed/yXmNmckX4sI}
@item
Hash Tables and Hash Functions @uref{https://www.youtube.com/embed/KyUTuwz_b7Q}
@item
Hashing: The Greatest Idea in Programming @uref{https://www.i-programmer.info/babbages-bag/479-hashing.html}
@end itemize

@node O(n@math{^2})
@section O(n@math{^2})

@cindex Big-O Complexity
@cindex Dictionary
In the current implementation, every file, indeed @emph{every chunk}, is compared to every other file and chunk. This is the equivalent of using bubble sort, which is never a good idea and absolutely positively definitely never ever @emph{ever} a good idea if you are planning to process Big Data. With hash functions we have introduced the idea of a ``fingerprint'', and the logical next step is to keep a list of all fingerprints @emph{and where they came from}. If the same fingerprint have two (or more) origins, it is a clone, which is what was to be shown. The data structure, for you algorithms and data structure nerds out there, is a @emph{Dictionary}, where the key is the hash value of the chunk of code and the values are the locations where this key can be found.

@example
    Key        - Values
|
+-- AEF623...  - File GH/line 4-8 
|                                    
+-- 1ED322...  - File AK/line 25-29, File AK/line 48-52
|                                                      
+-- GJHT55...  - File OB/line 12-16
|                                  
+-- MH6555...  - File NJ/line 56-60
|                                  
+-- 7878GF...  - File KI/line 4-9, File KI/line 88-92, File OO/line 4-9
|                                                                      
+-- 0D21HG...  - File MK/line 89-93              
|
@end example

The overall process for each file now becomes:

@enumerate
@item
Generate chunks and transform each chunk into a hash value.
@item
Add the tuple @code{<hash value, file location>} to the Dictionary Of All Chunks
@item
Filter the Dictionary Of All Chunks so that only entries with more than one value remains. These are candidate Clones.
@item
For each remaining @code{file location}, find all adjacent file locations and expand the candidate Clones accordingly.
@item
Repeat until no more adjacent file locations. What remains are unique and expanded Clones.
@item
For each Clone, use the @code{file location} to extract the original source code for the clone; add this to the Clone.
@item
Add to list of identified Clones.
@item
Repeat.
@end enumerate

There is an opportunity to optimise in steps 2 and 3 so that we keep track of only the currently processed file. Otherwise, the expand function in step 4 will take much longer.

The implementation of hash tables such as this are usually quite optimised for finding elements (or where to write a new element), bringing these operations down to a best case Big-O complexity of @code{O(log n)} (which assumes that all your trees are balanced and the wind is blowing in the right direction. The bottom line is that we can't really improve the @emph{writing} any further).

@node From File-by-File to All-at-Once Analysis
@section From File-by-File to All-at-Once Analysis

@cindex Breadth-First Analysis
@cindex File-by-File Analysis
@cindex All-at-Once Analysis
The elephant in the room remains. We are still processing one file at the time, so the overall complexity is still stuck to the bubble-sort @code{O(n^2)} quagmire. This is kind of the whole point with this exercise: In order to get any further, we need to re-think the problem. The @emph{file} is no longer the most appropriate data ``atom'', even if we still have to start (and end) there. The algorithm we are looking for now would be to:

@enumerate
@item
For All Files At Once, generate chunks and transform each chunk into a hash value.
@item
For All Chunks (now only a hash value and a location), Add the tuple @code{<hash value, file location>} to the Dictionary Of All Chunks.
@item
Filter the Dictionary Of All Chunks so that only entries with more than one value remains. These are candidate Clones.
@item
For each remaining @code{file location}, find all adjacent file locations and expand the candidate Clones accordingly.
@item
Repeat until no more adjacent file locations. What remains are unique and expanded Clones.
@item
For each Clone, use the @code{file location} to extract the original source code for the clone; add this to the Clone.
@item
Add to list of identified Clones.
@end enumerate

It turns out we were almost there! Steps 1 and 2 are modified to work on all files at once, and the expand in step 4 remains a challenge. 

@strong{Map and Reduce}
Before continuing, we need to introduce the functional programming concept of MapReduce (Also mentioned as a Cloud Architecture Pattern in the Cloud Provisioning and Orchestration part of the course). The basic trick is to stop thinking about iterations and procedures where you @emph{first} do something and @emph{then} do something else. Instead, with functional programming you spend more time describing what the input data looks like, and how you want the output data to look like. Once you know this, you write a function to get from the input data to the output data and @emph{map} it onto your entire collection.

@itemize
@item
@code{map()} applies a given function element by element to a collection of elements and returns a collection of new (or modified) elements.
@item
@code{reduce()} aggregates the list of results from @code{map()} into a single result.
@end itemize

These two simple principles (coupled with a bit of @code{filter()}, @code{find()} , @code{exists()} , etc.) are surprisingly versatile for data analysis problems. Sometimes (as with the clone detection algorithm discussed so far), the problem or the required input and output data formats need to be rephrased a bit, but once you do the world's your oyster. Even better, @code{map()} can easily be parallelised since each element should be transformable by itself. The @code{reduce()} can also be parallelised, but this requires a bit more work. Being so very versatile, it is no surprise that you will find implementations of MapReduce in places such as databases and in many programming languages (such as lisp, of course, but also Java 8's Streams API @uref{http://winterbe.com/posts/2014/07/31/java8-stream-tutorial-examples/}, and in JavaScript @uref{https://www.sitepoint.com/map-reduce-functional-javascript/} ).

Let's try to turn the previous algorithm into something MapReduceable. While we are at it, we also need to acknowledge that not all things should be solved by @emph{our} programming. Some tasks are better left to a database.

@table @asis
@item Map
Transform
@table @asis
@item Input
Array of files
@item Output
Array of Chunks containing @code{@{filename, startLine, endLine, contentHash@}}
@item Comment
Technically, the output is an Array of Arrays of Chunks, but this is quickly flattened into an Array of Chunks.
@item Side Effect
Files is stored somewhere accessible (e.g. a database)
@end table

@item Reduce
Merge output from Transform map
@table @asis
@item Input
Array(s) of Chunks
@item Output
Dictionary of @code{<contentHash , Array of Chunks>}
@item Comment
Just storing the chunks to a database will take care of this step for us.
@end table

@item Filter
Match Detection
@table @asis
@item Input
Dictionary of @code{<contentHash, Array of Chunks>}
@item Output
Dictionary of @code{<contentHash, Array of Chunks>} where Array of Chunks has length > 1.
@item Comment
This is a simple database search.
@end table

@item Reduce
Expand
@table @asis
@item Input
Dictionary of @code{<contentHash, Array of Chunks>} where Array of Chunks has length > 1.
@item Output
Array of Clones containing @code{Array of cloneInstances @{filename, startLine, endLine@}}
@item Comment
As we will see, this is the real killer. We will study two ways of addressing this step.
@end table

@item Map
Format
@table @asis
@item Input
Array of Clones AND Access to files
@item Output
Array of Clones containing @code{@{ Array of cloneInstances, sourceCode @}}
@item Comment
This is strictly not needed; the clones are already identified by the previous reduce, but can be solved with a database join.
@end table

@item Reduce
Merge output from Format map
@table @asis
@item Input
Array(s) of Clones
@item Output
Array of Clones
@item Comment
Only needed if the previous map is done in parallel.
@end table
@end table

A comment on the @samp{Filter} Step: If we do decide to implement this ourselves instead of relying on a database, this can be done as a Map (returning null if @code{Array.length == 1}) or (better but less parallelisable) as a Reduce.

@cindex Split Size
When parallelising a @code{map()} operation, the input is typically split into several parts, each of which is executed by a separate computing unit. In the extreme case there is one computing unit per entry in the input (e.g. when using Azure Functions or Amazon Lambdas). However, to minimise overhead costs of distributing data, running a function, and collecting the results, it may be desirable to instead distribute a block of data to each computing unit. With many frameworks, optimising the @samp{split size} is an important step of fine-tuning the performance of a big data analysis.

With several computing units, each executing their own @code{map()} on a section of the data, it becomes evident that the outputs from each computing unit need to be merged. Not all MapReduce frameworks leave the data in a nice state; expect to see a series of Arrays simply concatenated together even if the next step requires the input data to be at least sorted.

@node Wisely and slow They stumble that run fast
@section Wisely, and slow. They stumble that run fast.

Shakespeare be damned, we @emph{do} want this to run fast. And in parallel. And be distributable. So which programming language should we choose for this?

@findex JavaScript Promises
Until now, JavaScript have served us well. Map and Reduce are part of the standard feature set for JavaScript, and with Promises it is also possible to run the @code{map()} in parallel, but not distributed (granted, there are some open source packages for distributed MapReduce, but most of the ones I could find were last modified around 2018). Moreover, the general consensus of The Internet is that one does not reach for JavaScript when building a high performance computing solution. So let's explore the options.

We @emph{could} go down the rabbit hole and implement everything in C or C++ (@code{std::transform} and @code{std::reduce} were added in C++17), but I am not in the mood to go hunting for memory leaks, and distribution remains an issue.

@findex Java Streams
@pindex Apache Hadoop
@pindex Apache Spark
@pindex Apache Storm
Java? With Java 8 and the Streams API, there is a native implementation of MapReduce, as well as support for working with infinite data streams. Writing in Java would also have the benefit of opening up to many of the Apache Software Foundation's data processing tools such as Hadoop @uref{https://hadoop.apache.org/}, Spark @uref{https://spark.apache.org/}, or Storm @uref{https://storm.apache.org/index.html}.

@cindex Downsides with Apache Tools
The downside with all three of these, in my humble opinion, is that none of them are ready to be released outside of a university lab. Setting them up and actually getting the master node and worker nodes to communicate is @emph{painful}. There is no reliable list of which network ports that need to be open on each type of node in the network, the used network ports change between versions (even minor versions), and by default you need to essentially keep all ports above 10000 open (and hope that this is sufficient; the port to use for a particular job is assigned at random and sometimes you get a port number lower than 10000). Older versions communicated via unencrypted http requests without any authentication. And even when you do have everything up and running, Hadoop MapReduce will fail three times out of ten (I know: I have tested).

