@anchor{elegant-expansion}
The @emph{elegant} way to expand clones is by using a @code{reduce} operation like so:

@findex expand-clones-elegantly
@example
(defn expand-clones-elegantly [candidates]
  (reduce (fn [clones candidate]
            (let [@{overlapping true remaining false@} (group-by 
                                                      #(overlaps? candidate %)
                                                      clones)]
              (if (empty? overlapping)
                  (conj clones candidate)
                  (conj remaining (reduce merge-clones candidate overlapping)))
            )) [] candidates))
@end example

In plaintext: with every candidate, split the already found clones into two piles (This is what the @code{group-by} does; One that overlaps the new candidate (all elements where @code{overlaps?} evaluates to @code{true}) and one with all the remaining clones (where @code{overlaps?} evaluates to @code{false} ). If there are no overlapping clones, this is a new clone and is conjoined to the existing list of clones. Otherwise, we want to remove the overlapping clones (conveniently already done with the @code{remaining} list) and just store a new clone that merges all of the overlapping clones into one. Beautiful, isn't it? This is the version that fails above.

@cindex Performance Antipattern
@cindex Performance Antipattern "Ramp"
As it turns out, this introduces a performance antipattern called ``The Ramp''. Every new candidate that does not overlap any existing clones will add one more item to the list of clones. Sometimes a few items are removed, but most of the time the list of clones just grow. The time it takes to @code{group-by} thus gets longer and longer all the time like a ramp: it starts out small but grows continually. Eventually something has to break:

