@node Expand with ``Aleph-null Bottles of Beer''
@section Expand with ``Aleph-null Bottles of Beer''

@anchor{beer-expansion}
The alternative to being elegant is inspired by an ancient song (who knew that @emph{this} was Billy Bones' true treasure!):

@display
Lots and lots of candidates on the wall!
Take one down,
stretch it abound,
store it as a clone,
and remove what we found.
@end display

Translate this to Clojure, and we get the following:

@findex expand-clones
@findex maybe-expand
@example
(defn maybe-expand [dbconnection candidate]
  (loop [overlapping (storage/get-overlapping-candidates dbconnection candidate)
         clone candidate]
    (if (empty? overlapping)
      (do
        (storage/remove-overlapping-candidates! dbconnection (list candidate))
        clone)
      (let [merged-clone (reduce merge-clones clone overlapping)]
        (storage/remove-overlapping-candidates! dbconnection overlapping)
        (recur (storage/get-overlapping-candidates dbconnection merged-clone)
               merged-clone)))))

(defn expand-clones []
  (let [dbconnection (storage/get-dbconnection)]
    (loop [candidate (storage/get-one-candidate dbconnection)]
      (when candidate
        (storage/store-clone! dbconnection (maybe-expand dbconnection candidate))
        (recur (storage/get-one-candidate dbconnection))))))
@end example

Where:
@itemize
@item
In @code{expand-clones} we ``take one down'' as long as we can find one. @code{maybe-expand} ``stretches it abound'' and then we store it as a clone.
@item
In @code{maybe-expand} we find any candidates that overlap and stretch our clone to encompass these too (in @code{merged-clone}). Removing all the ``used'' candidates from the database as we go, we then loop back to see if the newly stretched clone happen to overlap with any new candidates.
@item
The two clojure commands @code{loop} and @code{recur} go hand in hand to overcome the principle of immutable data by replacing iterations with recursion.
@end itemize

